Let (S \triangleleft P, \iota ^S, \sigma ^S, \text {pr}^S) and (T \triangleleft Q, \iota ^T, \sigma ^T, \text {pr}^T) be monad containers, where S \triangleleft P satisfies S3 (for s, f) and the singleton properties, and T \triangleleft Q has a constant t_0. We have:
\begin {align*} &u_1\ s\ (\lambda p' . \begin {cases} t_0 & \text {if } p' = p\\ \iota ^T & \text {otherwise} \end {cases})\\ &= u_1\ s\ (\lambda p' . \begin {cases} u_1\ \iota ^S\ (\lambda \_ . t_0) & \text {if } p' = p\\ u_1\ (f\ p')\ (\lambda \_ . \iota ^T) & \text {otherwise} \end {cases})\\ &= u_1\ s\ (\lambda p' . u_1\ (\begin {cases} \iota ^S & \text {if } p' = p\\ (f\ p') & \text {otherwise} \end {cases})\ (\lambda \_ . \begin {cases} t_0 & \text {if } p' = p\\ \iota ^T & \text {otherwise} \end {cases}))\\ &= u_1\ (\sigma ^S\ s\ (\lambda p' . \begin {cases} \iota ^S & \text {if } p' = p\\ (f\ p') & \text {otherwise} \end {cases}))\ (\lambda p'' . \begin {cases} t_0 & \text {if } \text {pr}^S_1\ p'' = p\\ \iota ^T & \text {otherwise} \end {cases})\\ &= u_1\ \iota ^S\ (\lambda \_ . \begin {cases} t_0 & \text {if } * = *\\ \iota ^T & \text {otherwise} \end {cases})\\ &= t_0 \end {align*}
This lets us prove that: \sigma \ (\iota ^T , \lambda \_ . s)\ (\lambda p' . \begin {cases} (t_0 , \lambda \_ . \iota ^S) & \text {if } \pi _2\ p' = p\\ \iota & \text {otherwise} \end {cases}) = (t_0 , \lambda \_ . \iota ^S) for any compatible composite of type T \triangleleft Q \circ S \triangleleft P.

In monad container language: (S \triangleleft P, \iota , \sigma , \text {pr}) satisfies the "disjoint substitution condition" if for all shapes s, s_0 : S, positions p : P\ s, functions f : P\ s \to S where f\ p = \iota , and functions g : P\ s \to S where:
\begin {align*} g\ p &:= s_0\\ g\ p' &:= \iota \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \text {if } p' \neq p \end {align*}
then we have: \sigma \ (\sigma \ s\ g)\ (f \circ \text {pr}_1) = \sigma \ (\sigma \ s\ f)\ (g \circ \text {pr}_1)

(S \triangleleft  P, \iota , \sigma , \text {pr}) satisfies absorbtion (TODO: not a good name!) if there exist an s : S, and f : P\ s \to  S such that for any p : P\ s we have:
           \sigma \ s\ f^{p} = \iota      
    using the shorthand:
           f^p := \lambda  p' .        \begin {cases}         \iota  & \text {if } p' = p\\         f\ p' & \text {otherwise}       \end {cases}

Let S \triangleleft  P be a container. A monad container (or mnd-container) [uustalu2017] on S \triangleleft  P is given by the following data:
       \begin {align*}       \iota  &: S\\       \sigma  &: \prod _{s : S} (P\ s \to  S) \to  S\\       \text {pr} &: \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to  S\}} P\ (\sigma \ s\ f) \to  \sum _{p : P\ s} P\ (f\ p)     \end {align*}   
  For which the following laws hold:
       \begin {align*}       \sigma \ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \iota  ) &= a\\       \text {pr}_1\ p &= p\\       \sigma \ \iota \ (\lambda  \_ . a ) &= a\\       \text {pr}_2\ p &= p\\       \sigma \ (\sigma \ a\ f)\ (\lambda  p . g\ (\text {pr}_1\ p)\ (\text {pr}_2\ p)) &= \sigma \ a\ (\lambda  p . \sigma \ (f\ p)\ (g\ p))\\       \text {pr}_1\ (\text {pr}_1\ p) &= \text {pr}_1\ p\\       \text {pr}_1\ (\text {pr}_2\ p) &= \text {pr}_2\ (\text {pr}_1\ p)\\       \text {pr}_2\ p &= \text {pr}_2\ (\text {pr}_2\ p)     \end {align*}   
  We abbreviate \pi _1 \circ  \text {pr} as \text {pr}_1 and \pi _2 \circ  \text {pr} as \text {pr}_2. Each set of laws for \text {pr} hold up to the laws for \sigma  above them.
